{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486839"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:46:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:46:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"186"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"186","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/186"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.03,0.05,0.16,0.57]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"186"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77169"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"186","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/186"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"186"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62676"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"130"},{"type":"tags","id":"1074"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1750"},{"type":"tags","id":"2697"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"74"},{"type":"contributions","id":"510"},{"type":"contributions","id":"581"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39506"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41440"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77169"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 46-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a frontal headache, sweating and palpitations. She has experienced four similar episodes over the past few months, but this episode is the most severe. She has a family history of primary hyperparathyroidism, with her mother being diagnosed at a young age. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She does not drink alcohol or take recreational drugs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears anxious and diaphoretic with a fine bilateral hand tremor. Her pulse rate is 118/min and regular, blood pressure 160/100 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Heart sounds are dual with no murmurs. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable. Venous blood gas shows no significant abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate pre-operative medication regimen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dexamethasone followed by hydrocortisone","Thiamine followed by diazepam","Normal saline followed by insulin infusion","Hydralazine followed by sodium nitroprusside","Phenoxybenzamine followed by atenolol"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of pheochromocytoma: headaches, palpitations, and diaphoresis. The episodic nature of symptoms and family history of endocrine disease (primary hyperparathyroidism) raises suspicion for Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia (MEN) syndrome, making pheochromocytoma more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhenoxybenzamine followed by atenolol\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate pre-operative regimen. Alpha blockade must be established first to prevent unopposed alpha-adrenergic stimulation. Beta blockers are then added to control reflex tachycardia. This typically takes 1-2 weeks to achieve adequate blood pressure control before surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDexamethasone followed by hydrocortisone\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for treating an Addisonian crisis, which presents with hypotension, shock, and electrolyte disturbances rather than hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThiamine followed by diazepam\u003C/strong\u003E is the treatment for alcohol withdrawal syndrome. While this can present with sympathetic overactivity, the patient has no history of alcohol use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal saline followed by insulin infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is the standard treatment for diabetic ketoacidosis, which would present with hyperglycaemia, ketosis, and metabolic acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydralazine followed by sodium nitroprusside\u003C/strong\u003E might be used in hypertensive emergency, but would not address the underlying catecholamine excess of pheochromocytoma. These agents could potentially worsen hemodynamic instability.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alpha blockade must be established before beta blockade in pheochromocytoma to avoid unopposed alpha-adrenergic stimulation.","The classic triad of pheochromocytoma consists of headaches, palpitations, and diaphoresis.","Family history of endocrine disorders should raise suspicion for inherited syndromes associated with pheochromocytoma."],"references":["Tsirlin A, Oo Y, Sharma R, Kansara A, Gliwa A, Banerji MA. Pheochromocytoma: A Review. Maturitas. 2014;77(3):229-38. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24472290/","Lenders JW, Duh QY, Eisenhofer G, Gimenez-Roqueplo AP, Grebe SK, Murad MH, et al. Pheochromocytoma and paraganglioma: an Endocrine Society clinical practice guideline. J Clin Endocrinol Metab 2014;99(6):1915\u201342. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24893135/","Management of phaeochromocytoma. In: eTG complete [online]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited [online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.tg.org.au","Marik PE, Varon J. Hypertensive crises: challenges and management. Chest 2007;131(6):1949\u201362. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17565029/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62676"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"186"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62676"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T11:03:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-22T20:44:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"186"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77169"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"p